		<item>
		<title>
		By: Mark Hiscocks		</title>
		<link>/2008/07/checkboxes-legacy-or-innovation/#comment-315</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Mark Hiscocks]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 27 Oct 2009 12:19:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">/wordpress/?p=396#comment-315</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I&#039;ll prefix my comments by saying that the majority of my development has occurred on the desktop side of things although I have been developing for the web for the past couple of years.

I personally it difficult to look past the fact that checkboxes have traditionally been used to indicate positive/affirmative states. For instance:
  - CHECK -&#062; I want Option 1
  - CHECK -&#062; I want Option 2
  - UNCHECK -&#062; I do not want Option 3

Using the above e-mail examples, I find it slightly counterintuitive to use checkboxes to indicate selection for a negative action, e.g. checking e-mails to delete them. When a list exists from which items are being removed, I’ve seen users get confused by whether checking an item will maintain its existence on a list or whether checking an item will cause it to be removed. The question ends up being: Am I checking it to keep it or am I checking it to get rid of it? I know that people are thinking “Well, you’ve checked an item to indicate it for inclusion for deletion”, but anecdotal experience has sometimes shown otherwise.

Although checkboxes make some things easier, they can complicate other UI interactions.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ll prefix my comments by saying that the majority of my development has occurred on the desktop side of things although I have been developing for the web for the past couple of years.</p>
<p>I personally it difficult to look past the fact that checkboxes have traditionally been used to indicate positive/affirmative states. For instance:<br />
  &#8211; CHECK -&gt; I want Option 1<br />
  &#8211; CHECK -&gt; I want Option 2<br />
  &#8211; UNCHECK -&gt; I do not want Option 3</p>
<p>Using the above e-mail examples, I find it slightly counterintuitive to use checkboxes to indicate selection for a negative action, e.g. checking e-mails to delete them. When a list exists from which items are being removed, I’ve seen users get confused by whether checking an item will maintain its existence on a list or whether checking an item will cause it to be removed. The question ends up being: Am I checking it to keep it or am I checking it to get rid of it? I know that people are thinking “Well, you’ve checked an item to indicate it for inclusion for deletion”, but anecdotal experience has sometimes shown otherwise.</p>
<p>Although checkboxes make some things easier, they can complicate other UI interactions.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
