					<description><![CDATA[I found another example of the checkbox/selection paradigm that I commented about earlier: The calendars option in Apple&#039;s iCal. The checkboxes control which calendars are displayed. The selection of the actual item indicates which single calendar is &quot;active&quot; - i.e. which calendar a new appointments will be added to by default.

Here&#039;s a screenshot:
http://www.antunkarlovac.com/stuff/apple_ical_checkbox_selection.png

I started using a Mac (along with iCal) several months ago, and never paid attention to this. I guess that means it felt natural to me. Of course, since Apple designed this UI, it must certainly be beyond dispute.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I found another example of the checkbox/selection paradigm that I commented about earlier: The calendars option in Apple&#8217;s iCal. The checkboxes control which calendars are displayed. The selection of the actual item indicates which single calendar is &#8220;active&#8221; &#8211; i.e. which calendar a new appointments will be added to by default.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s a screenshot:<br />
<a href="http://www.antunkarlovac.com/stuff/apple_ical_checkbox_selection.png" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.antunkarlovac.com/stuff/apple_ical_checkbox_selection.png</a></p>
<p>I started using a Mac (along with iCal) several months ago, and never paid attention to this. I guess that means it felt natural to me. Of course, since Apple designed this UI, it must certainly be beyond dispute.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
