		<item>
		<title>
		By: Sarah		</title>
		<link>/2008/07/checkboxes-legacy-or-innovation/#comment-311</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Sarah]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 26 Jul 2008 03:00:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">/wordpress/?p=396#comment-311</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[My main point was in using checkboxes for select and multi-select, instead of the standard desktop convention of click and ctrl/shift-click.  I can&#039;t think of places I&#039;ve seen that besides webmail, but I wouldn&#039;t be surprised if it is used elsewhere.

If you are talking about this kind of permissions:  &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/linuxjournal/articles/087/8710/8710f3.inline.png&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/linuxjournal/articles/087/8710/8710f3.inline.png&lt;/a&gt;
Then checkboxes are being used in a standard way where they represent a true/false attribute of an object.  I think the visual design of that particular UI could be improved for clarity and readability, but I see that as a standard use of checkboxes.
]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>My main point was in using checkboxes for select and multi-select, instead of the standard desktop convention of click and ctrl/shift-click.  I can&#8217;t think of places I&#8217;ve seen that besides webmail, but I wouldn&#8217;t be surprised if it is used elsewhere.</p>
<p>If you are talking about this kind of permissions:  <a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/linuxjournal/articles/087/8710/8710f3.inline.png" rel="nofollow">http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/linuxjournal/articles/087/8710/8710f3.inline.png</a><br />
Then checkboxes are being used in a standard way where they represent a true/false attribute of an object.  I think the visual design of that particular UI could be improved for clarity and readability, but I see that as a standard use of checkboxes.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
